"Zhou D.K., Larar A.M., Liu X., Smith W.L., Strow L.L., Yang P., Schlüssel P., Calbet X.","Global land surface emissivity retrieved from satellite ultraspectral IR measurements",2011,"IEEE Transactions on Geoscience and Remote Sensing","49","4", 5523979,"1277","1290",,,10.1109/TGRS.2010.2051036,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-79953210715&partnerID=40&md5=4b6c7d0c5991a1ad33d6eea3c8c08c6c","NASA Langley Research Center, Hampton, VA 23681, United States; Hampton University, Hampton, VA 23668, United States; University of Wisconsin-Madison, Madison, WI 53706, United States; University of Maryland-Baltimore County, Baltimore, MD 21250, United States; Texas A and M University, College Station, TX 77843, United States; European Organisation for the Exploitation of Meteorological Satellites (EUMETSAT), 64295 Darmstadt, Germany","Zhou, D.K., NASA Langley Research Center, Hampton, VA 23681, United States; Larar, A.M., NASA Langley Research Center, Hampton, VA 23681, United States; Liu, X., NASA Langley Research Center, Hampton, VA 23681, United States; Smith, W.L., Hampton University, Hampton, VA 23668, United States, University of Wisconsin-Madison, Madison, WI 53706, United States; Strow, L.L., University of Maryland-Baltimore County, Baltimore, MD 21250, United States; Yang, P., Texas A and M University, College Station, TX 77843, United States; Schlüssel, P., European Organisation for the Exploitation of Meteorological Satellites (EUMETSAT), 64295 Darmstadt, Germany; Calbet, X., European Organisation for the Exploitation of Meteorological Satellites (EUMETSAT), 64295 Darmstadt, Germany","Ultraspectral resolution infrared (IR) radiances obtained from nadir observations provide information about the atmosphere, surface, aerosols, and clouds. Surface spectral emissivity (SSE) and surface skin temperature from current and future operational satellites can and will reveal critical information about the Earth's ecosystem and land-surface-type properties, which might be utilized as a means of long-term monitoring of the Earth's environment and global climate change. In this study, fast radiative transfer models applied to the atmosphere under all weather conditions are used for atmospheric profile and surface or cloud parameter retrieval from ultraspectral and/or hyperspectral spaceborne IR soundings. An inversion scheme, dealing with cloudy as well as cloud-free radiances observed with ultraspectral IR sounders, has been developed to simultaneously retrieve atmospheric thermodynamic and surface or cloud microphysical parameters. This inversion scheme has been applied to the Infrared Atmospheric Sounding Interferometer (IASI). Rapidly produced SSE is initially evaluated through quality control checks on the retrievals of other impacted surface and atmospheric parameters. Initial validation of retrieved emissivity spectra is conducted with Namib and Kalahari desert laboratory measurements. Seasonal products of global land SSE and surface skin temperature retrieved with IASI are presented to demonstrate seasonal variation of SSE. © 2006 IEEE.","Infrared (IR) ultraspectral sounder; inversion; remote sensing; surface emissivity; temperature","Atmospheric parameters; Atmospheric profile; Cloud microphysical parameters; Cloud parameter retrieval; Critical information; Emissivity spectra; Global climate changes; Global land surface; HyperSpectral; Infrared atmospheric sounding interferometers; inversion; Inversion scheme; IR measurements; Kalahari; Laboratory measurements; Long term monitoring; Nadir observations; Radiative transfer model; Seasonal product; Seasonal variation; Space-borne; Spectral emissivity; surface emissivity; Surface skin temperature; Ultraspectral; Ultraspectral sounder; Weather conditions; Acoustic devices; Climate change; Earth (planet); Electromagnetic wave emission; Infrared imaging; Quality control; Radiative transfer; Remote sensing; Surface properties; Temperature; aerosol; climate change; cloud microphysics; emissivity; infrared radiation; land surface; remote sensing; seasonal variation; spectral resolution; surface temperature; temperature inversion; Kalahari Desert; Namib Desert; Namibia",,,,,,"Chahine, M.T., Pagano, T.S., Aumann, H.H., Atlas, R., Barnet, C., Blaisdell, J., Chen, L., Zhou, L., Improving weather forecasting and providing new data on greenhouse gases (2006) Bulletin of the American Meteorological Society, 87 (7), pp. 911-926. , DOI 10.1175/BAMS-87-7-911; Blumstein, D., Chalon, G., Carlier, T., Buil, C., Hebert, Ph., Maciaszek, T., Ponce, G., Jegou, R., IASI instrument: Technical overview and measured performances (2004) Proceedings of SPIE - The International Society for Optical Engineering, 5543, pp. 196-207. , DOI 10.1117/12.560907, 22, Infrared Spaceborne Remote Sensing XII; Klaes, K.D., Cohen, M., Buhler, Y., Schlussel, P., Munro, R., Luntama, J.-P., Von Engeln, A., Schmetz, J., An introduction to the Eumetsat polar system (2007) Bulletin of the American Meteorological Society, 88 (7), pp. 1085-1096. , DOI 10.1175/BAMS-88-7-1085; Schadlich, S., Gottsche, F.M., Olesen, F.-S., Influence of land surface parameters and atmosphere on METEOSAT brightness temperatures and generation of land surface temperature maps by temporally and spatially interpolating atmospheric correction (2001) Remote Sensing of Environment, 75 (1), pp. 39-46. , DOI 10.1016/S0034-4257(00)00154-1, PII S0034425700001541; Zhou, D.K., Smith, W.L., Li, J., Howell, H.B., Cantwell, G.W., Larar, A.M., Knuteson, R.O., Mango, S.A., Thermodynamic product retrieval methodology and validation for NAST-I (2002) Applied Optics, 41 (33), pp. 6957-6967; Borel, C.C., Surface emissivity and temperature retrieval for a hyperspectral sensor (1998) Proc. Geosci. Remote Sens. Symp., 1, pp. 546-549; Péquignot, E., Chédin, A., Scott, N.A., Infrared continental surface emissivity spectra retrieved from AIRS hyperspectral sensor (2008) J. Appl. Meteorol. Climatol., 47 (6), pp. 1619-1633. , Jun; 